                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 1.  <span>Schematic representation of the current understanding of erythropoiesis.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>Hematopoietic stem cells exist in two distinct compartments: cells in N<sub>2</sub> are actively replicating and contributing to blood cell formation.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p2" name="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p2"></a><p>They are supported by a larger quiescent pool (N<sub>1</sub>).</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p3" name="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p3"></a><p>Cell replication leads to an exponential amplification (2<sup>K</sup>) of progeny that ultimately differentiate into the various types of cells present in the circulation.</p>
